The '''2017 Southern Thailand floods''' occurred from December 2016 throughout early months of 2017 and are the biggest floods in over 30 years in the southern part of the country during the regional annual monsoon season, which is distinct from other parts of the nation and mirrors that the [[Malay Peninsula]]. They have also caused damages in [[Kelantan]] and [[Terengganu]] states in Malaysia the weeks prior. The floods began in early January. Some 120 billion baht ($4 billion USD) in damages are foreseen as of mid-January, much of this due to lost production in agriculture tourism and infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web|title=Thailand: Floods - Dec 2016|url=http://reliefweb.int/disaster/fl-2017-000004-tha|publisher=Reliefweb|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> [[Rubber]] supply is particularly impacted. The death toll have reached 91.<ref>{{cite web|title=Flood toll: 85 killed, 4 missing|url=https://www.thephuketnews.com/flood-toll-85-killed-4-missing-60735.php|publisher=The Phuket Post|accessdate=23 January 2017}}</ref> Particularly hard hit are palm and rubber plantations.<ref>{{cite web|title=Southern flood damage could reach B120bn|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/business/news/1181792/southern-flood-damage-could-reach-b120bn|publisher=Bangkok Post|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref>
