{{about||the British actor|Jack Livesey|the English footballer|Jack Livesey (footballer)}}

'''John "Jack" Livesey''' (born 15 May 1954) is a British [[military imposter]] who posed as a decorated war hero; in actuality he served in the army as a cook for three years. His fabricated military record included twenty years in the [[Parachute Regiment (United Kingdom)|Parachute Regiment]], fighting with the [[2nd Battalion, Parachute Regiment|2nd Battalion]] in the [[Falklands War]], serving five tours of duty in [[Northern Ireland]], receiving the [[Military Medal]] and reaching the rank of [[Colour Sergeant]]. He has worked as a historian, author, consultant, lecturer and battlefield tour guide on the basis of his alleged military experience.<ref name="BBC News">{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/cambridgeshire/8130351.stm |title=Historian 'posed as a war hero'  |newspaper=BBC News |date=3 July 2009}}</ref>

== Career ==
Jack Livesey served as a chef in the [[Army Catering Corps]] from 1971 until 1974, when he was discharged following a mental breakdown. Livesey admitted that he created a 'fantasy world' to compensate for his early discharge from the army: 'I built this fictional guy up which was better than admitting the failure that was my military career […] It wasn’t the best way to end your military career. It was going to be my dream – the Army was a wonderful life and I screwed it up and created this fantasy'.<ref name="Daily Mail">{{cite news |url= http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2021592/Benefits-cheat-John-Livesey-escaped-jail-thanks-fantasy-Falklands-heroics.html |title= Benefits cheat John Livesey escaped jail thanks to fantasy Falklands heroics is exposed as a liar  |newspaper=Daily Mail |date=3 July 2009}}</ref>

Livesey was featured as a military historian in the documentary ''Death and Destruction in the Falaise Gap''<ref name="Death and Destruction in the Falaise Gap">{{cite video|title=Death and Destruction in the Falaise Gap|medium=DVD|publisher=DD Home Entertainment}}</ref> and on [[History (U.S. TV channel)|the History Channel]] series ''[[Battlefield Detectives]]''. He worked as a historical adviser on the 2005 [[BBC]] documentary series ''D-Day to Berlin'' and the 2006 movie ''[[Flyboys (film)|Flyboys]]''.<ref name="imdb">{{IMDb name|2710612}}</ref> He claimed to have also advised production crews, uncredited, on the miniseries ''[[Band of Brothers (miniseries)|Band of Brothers]]'' and the movie ''[[Saving Private Ryan]]''.<ref name="BBC News2">{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-cambridgeshire-14683750 |title= Army fantasist John Livesey jailed for lying to court  |newspaper=BBC News |date=26 August 2011}}</ref>

Livesey authored books of military non-fiction, three which were co-written by [[George Forty]], a well-known author and a former curator of [[the Tank Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bournemouthecho.co.uk/news/features/obituaries/14534276.Lt_Col_George_Forty_____Father_of_the_Tank_Museum___/|title=Lt Col George Forty, "Father of the Tank Museum"|work=bournemouthecho.co.uk|accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref>

Livesey worked at the [[Imperial War Museum Duxford]] for seven years, first as a volunteer and later as a collections assistant, until he resigned in 2006.<ref name="BBC News"/>

== Criminal Convictions ==
In 2004 Jack Livesey was convicted of [[benefit fraud]] for receiving nearly £30,000 in [[incapacity benefit]] while he was employed at the Imperial War Museum. He was sentenced to a [[suspended sentence|suspended twelve-month jail term]] due to his supposed military service, and character references submitted by veterans including [[Air Commodore]] [[Peter Thorne (RAF officer)|Peter Thorne]] and Major [[Gordon Corrigan]], who knew Livesey and believed him to be a war hero.<ref name="Daily Mail"/>

Livesey was exposed as an impostor when investigations following his conviction found that the references submitted by the veterans were based on false claims that Livesey had made to them. He was subsequently charged with [[perverting the course of justice]] by police, and admitted to lying about his army career, but denied he was aware the references were submitted. His partner, Bridget Pollard, testified that she had compiled the references.<ref name="The Guardian">{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/aug/04/man-faked-army-career-guilty-perverting-justice |title= Man who faked army career guilty of perverting course of justice  |newspaper=The Guardian |date=4 August 2011}}</ref>

In mitigation, Livesey's attorney stated that his client had been diagnosed with [[dependent personality disorder|dependent]] and [[histrionic personality disorder]], and argued these disorders impaired his client's ability to tell fact from fiction. Livesey was found guilty, sentenced to three years in jail and was ordered to pay £3,500 in prosecution costs.<ref name="Mirror">{{cite news |url= https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/man-jailed-for-faking-army-career-185625 |title= Man jailed for faking army career  |newspaper=Mirror |date=7 February 2012}}</ref> He filed on appeal on the grounds that his sentence was excessive. The appeal was denied.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fake Falkland's war hero: sentence appeal dismissed|last=Brown|first=Raymond|publisher=''Cambridge News''|date=May 2, 2012}}</ref>

