{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}} [[Image:NZPWI_invitational 2006 poster.jpg|right]] The '''NZPWI Invitational''' was a [[professional wrestling]] [[pay-per-view]] (PPV) event hosted by the website New Zealand Pro Wrestling Informer (NZPWI). The event was the first interpromotional show ever held in New Zealand and featured wrestlers from the country's three major promotions [[Impact Pro Wrestling]], [[Kiwi Pro Wrestling]], [[New Zealand Wide Pro Wrestling]], and Peter Ball's Major Impact Wrestling from [[Australia]] now called [[Impact Pro Wrestling Australia]]. Held annually in 2006 and 2007, it was primarily a [[single-elimination tournament]] and included a 20-man [[battle royal]] semi-main event. The battle royal would end via pin or submission between the last two entrants, the winner of which would receive an entry for next year's invitational.<ref name="Alvarez">{{cite web |url=http://www.f4wonline.com/content/view/2127/1/ |title=Tuesday news: Drug testing, ECW tonight, Mexico, Tito vs. Ken rematch set, Tank to fight again, more |author=Alvarez, Bryan |authorlink=Bryan Alvarez |date=8 August 2006 |work=Wrestling Observer/Figure Four Online |publisher=F4Wonline.com |accessdate=8 July 2010}}</ref><ref name="McCracken">{{cite web |url=http://www.fighttimes.com/magazine/magazine.asp?article=520 |title=A New Tradition Begins as HAV Becomes NZPWI Invitational Grand Champion! |author=McCracken, Dion |date=August 2006 |work= |publisher=FightTimes.com |accessdate=8 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.throng.co.nz/sport/sky-1-nzpwi-invitational-pro-wrestling |title=Sky 1: NZPWI Invitational Pro-Wrestling |author= |date=13 July 2007 |work=TV Highlights |publisher=Throng.co.nz |accessdate=8 July 2010}}</ref><ref name="OWW">{{cite web |url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/nzpwi-invitational/ |title=NZPWI Invitational |author=Ogilvie, Steve |author2=Kirsty Quested |year=2007 |work=New Zealand Wrestling Promotions |publisher=OnlineWorldofWrestling.com |accessdate=8 July 2010}}</ref>
The event was largely organised by Dion McCraken, NZPWI editor-in-chief, whose intention was to bring attention to [[professional wrestling in New Zealand]]. Similar to the [[ECWA Super 8 Tournament|Super 8 Tournament]] in the United States or the [[Super J-Cup]] in Japan, it showcased the top talent of New Zealand's "big three" and provided the first major television exposure for many independent wrestlers in the [[Australasia|Australasian region]] since the days of [[Steve Rickard]]'s "[[On the Mat]]" during the 1980s. The show also served as a reunion of sorts for older veterans of the era. [[John da Silva]], a champion amateur and pro wrestler during the 1960s and 70s, was in attendance at the 2006 invitational and presented the trophy to "Heartless" Alfred Valentine after winning the tournament.<ref name="Alvarez"/><ref name="McCracken"/><ref name="Alvarez2">{{cite web |url=http://www.f4wonline.com/content/view/2161/105/ |title=Monday notes: Raw, major WWE show moved, the TNA INFERNO, more |author=Alvarez, Bryan |authorlink=Bryan Alvarez |date=14 August 2006 |work=Wrestling Observer/Figure Four Online |publisher=F4Wonline.com |accessdate=8 July 2010}}</ref><ref name="Csonka">{{cite web |url=http://www.411mania.com/politics/columns/44061 |title=Various News: WWE Mexican Tour Changes and More |author=Csonka, Larry |date=14 August 2004 |work=Columns |publisher=411mania.com |accessdate=8 July 2010}}</ref><ref name="OWW"/>
It was one of the largest show's ever held in New Zealand and the event received some coverage by the [[Media of New Zealand|national media]]. The 2006 NZPWI Invitational was promoted by ''Fight Times Magazine'' in March 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fighttimes.com/magazine/magazine.asp?article=500 |title=New Zealand Pro-Wrestling Returns To The "Big Time"! |author=McCracken, Dion |date=April 2006 |work= |publisher=FightTimes.com |accessdate=8 July 2010}}</ref> The Machine, an IPW wrestler and first entrant to battle royal, was featured in a [[Article (publishing)|cover story]] for the ''Horowhenua-Kapiti Weekend Chronicle'' on 29 July.<ref>{{cite news |title=Meet The Machine |author=Burt, Andrew |newspaper=Horowhenua-Kapiti Weekend Chronicle |date=29 July 2006 |url= }}</ref> Two of its participants, IPW wrestlers Alfred Valentine and Jon E. King, were interviewed on [[TV One (New Zealand)|TV One]]'s morning talk show ''Breakfast'' by [[Kay Gregory]] days prior to the event.<ref name="Alvarez"/><ref>{{Cite episode |title=Tuesday August&nbsp;8 |episodelink= |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/view/page/497100/809128 |series=Breakfast |serieslink= |credits=[[Kay Gregory]] (Interviewer) |network=[[Television New Zealand]] |station=[[TV One (New Zealand)|TV One]] |airdate=8 August 2006 |season= |seriesno= |number= |minutes= |quote=}}</ref>
The first annual NZPWI Invitational was held at the [[Lynfield, New Zealand|Lynfield]] [[YMCA]] on 12 August 2006, and was attended by a sell out crowd of 450 fans. It was the largest attendance for a live wrestling event in 20 years.<ref name="Csonka"/> The 2006 NZPWI Invitational was later shown on [[Sky1]] and proved so popular that the network aired on [[primetime]] the following year. The second show was broadcast following the 9 December 2007 edition of [[WWE Smackdown]],<ref name="OWW"/> and again on [[Christmas Eve]] followed by the [[WWE Hall of Fame|WWE Hall of Fame Induction Ceremony]]. The program was watched by over 100,000 people on [[SKY Network Television|SKY Television]] and both invitationals later released on DVD. Dion McCracken served as the [[colour commentator]] for both shows, with co-host [[Vinny Dunn]] in 2006 and manager Gary O. Davis in 2007, and his performance led to a full-time position as the head announcer of ''[[IPW Ignition]]''.
Although plans were made to hold a third NZPWI Invitational in November 2008, the event was unable to gain the necessary [[corporate sponsorship]] to cover costs. Previous shows had been held at a significant loss, costing at least $15,000 to run, and almost entirely supported financially by McCraken himself. Due to the financial burden, as well as familial commitments, McCraken officially announced on NZPWI.co.nz that he would no longer be able to host the event.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nzpwi.co.nz/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=4294&Itemid=78 |title=The end of the line for the NZPWI Invitational |author= |work= |publisher= |accessdate=8 July 2010}}</ref>
